>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde De Montoire was born in 1180, in Montoire, Loiret, Centre-Val de Loire, France, her father, Pierre de Montoire II, was 35 and her mother, Agnes Preuilly de Vendôme, was 30. She had at least 1 daughter with Geoffroy Ier de Palluau. She died in 1230, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1180–1230":"1180–1230","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1160–1235":"1160–1235","1175–1234":"1175–1234","1145–1201":"1145–1201","1150–1201":"1150–1201","1235":"1235","1201":"1201","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1174":"1174","1240":"1240","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Montoire, Loiret, Centre-Va